commentBody:
@Steven M.
As is often the case, it’s subjective.  My time today was closer to a pb than it was to my average.  
It’s all about the wavelength.

@Bruce  Sorry, that seems like it came out a bit snarkier than intended.

It seems like a lot of money to spend in order to have to maneuver and park a large vehicle, even though you have all your stuff with you. 

I did know someone who would drive one into the north Minnesota woods and then just park there for the summer like a cabin and use a car to get around.

@Bruce 

Another consideration is that using an RV allows you to take your pets with you.

That's a big deal if you're going to be traveling for more than a week or two.

@Rachel Yeah, renting one for Burning Man makes a lot of sense. 

I was thinking of (1) buying one, which means a minimum outlay of $20,000 and probably an average of more like $100,000, then (2) driving something that size around on an extended trip, sometimes in cities, finding places to park it in parking lots, finding places to hook up the water, electrical, and sewer lines, and (3) the cost of  repairs and rapid depreciation of its resale value.

One reason for my attitude about them is the fact that I'm just not in the same income bracket as a lot of you. I were to somehow gain a hundred grand it would probably partly go into structural repairs on my house, and partly to an investment fund for my sons.

@Linda Jo 

I guess the size of the thing would make a big difference, too. I've seen things like converted vans that wouldn't present nearly the same problems as, say, one built on a bus chassis.

My nightmare scenario would be driving one of the latter around Manhattan, looking for a parking space.

@Marshall Walthew 

I was never a big fan of Wham, though of course I was familiar with their (unavoidable) hit songs.

That said, the Wham documentary on Netflix is interesting a lot of fun!

